<subSubSection id="E1F4330180DF0BE844EEA296C4CDB2AC" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="9E0CDA4D9803EBA97FD7F0EA55FBAE65" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EDE5168687E12A59E9C5D1FDF9AA4F31" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Commonly collected genus of eucoilines throughout Africa, but particularly plentiful in equatorial Africa. The genus is common throughout the Old World Tropics as well as Mediterranean Africa. 
<bibRefCitation id="3C6D9A6DEC1EA65AA7DDA692423BDB59" author="Quinlan, J" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Historical series" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" pagination="243 - 366" title="A key to the Afrotropical genera of Eucoilidae (Hymenoptera), with a revision of certain genera." volume="52" year="1986">Quinlan (1986)</bibRefCitation>
made it a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="9C106D212BA6C5A1217DDA809902A3E9" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="6746EEA51D6DC7054FE0CBA6C3234714" originalValue="Förster">Foerster</normalizedToken>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="367EFEA872FCB9B4B56FC2CECA315818" author="Buffington, ML" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="589 - 601" title="A description of Aegeseucoela Buffington, new name, with taxonomic notes on the status of Gronotoma Foerster." volume="104" year="2002">Buffington (2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F81C6902ED3F010F6221A1CD28E6280C" author="Buffington, ML" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="239 - 290" title="Description, circumscription and phylogenetics of the Diglyphosematini Belizin, 1961, and the description of a new genus (Hymenoptera: Figitidae: Eucoilinae)." url="10.4289/0013-8797.113.3.239" volume="113" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
) followed this synonymy. The phylogenetic support for the inclusion of 
<taxonomicName id="F7FD94DEF6E89D337E93C42168CED9BE" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma nitida" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">Gronotoma nitida</taxonomicName>
Benoit (the only representative of 
<taxonomicName id="983CC0BBAFB6990AE3C632712E5B1057" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Afrostilba</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="EDFCC7450B0202166F545232B76E0530" author="Buffington, ML" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="239 - 290" title="Description, circumscription and phylogenetics of the Diglyphosematini Belizin, 1961, and the description of a new genus (Hymenoptera: Figitidae: Eucoilinae)." url="10.4289/0013-8797.113.3.239" volume="113" year="2011">Buffington 2011</bibRefCitation>
) in 
<taxonomicName id="779ABE88A21127A9B6AB475C35215EF9" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
s.str. was very weak; in that same work, it was noted that there is a distinct lineage of African species. After examination of much more recently collected material, it is clear that the African species reliably cluster with 
<bibRefCitation id="C40632F8A61F2B6EDFC67B0FFAD7AAC9" author="Benoit, PLG" journalOrPublisher="Annales Musee Royal du Congo Belge, Tervuren (serie 8)" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="532 - 550" title="Contributions a l'etude de la faune entomologique du Ruanda-Urundi (Mission P. Basilewsky 1953). CIX. HymenopteraCynipidae." volume="51" year="1956 a">
<normalizedToken id="7183BEBB12DE8C7C39EA85FE844C0277" originalValue="Benoit’s">Benoit's</normalizedToken>
(1956a)
</bibRefCitation>
generic concept of 
<taxonomicName id="182F6DC33185D29615B5AB45494CB1BE" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Afrostilba</taxonomicName>
. Examination of the type specimens of 
<bibRefCitation id="DAFE9DE87771BF5A411413B81C56BC87" author="Quinlan, J" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Historical series" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" pagination="243 - 366" title="A key to the Afrotropical genera of Eucoilidae (Hymenoptera), with a revision of certain genera." volume="52" year="1986">
<normalizedToken id="7CADDFB20434FCDE7B790669BC61BF8D" originalValue="Quinlan’s">Quinlan's</normalizedToken>
(1986)
</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName id="A6E53CBA61182A2ED024A4E574B4C41D" authority="Ashmead, 1887" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Eucoilidea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucoilidea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eucoilidea</taxonomicName>
species, as well as 
<taxonomicName id="823150DD34C8496064F0BE15B423E222" authority="Förster, 1869" authorityName="Förster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Diglyphosema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diglyphosema sensu" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">Diglyphosema sensu</taxonomicName>
Quinlan, has allowed us to make the new combinations below. Furthermore, examination of the type specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="C2FA826E3581CFE47750F27556961EDE" genus="Amphiglyphosema" lsidName="Amphiglyphosema" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" rank="genus">Amphiglyphosema</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E076AF6E505250878D7431E0768E1BB8" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba latesulcatum" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latesulcatum">Afrostilba latesulcatum</taxonomicName>
Benoit, allows us to synonymize 
<taxonomicName id="89E1CF2A82367B17B5B853E9DA9D12D0" genus="Amphiglyphosema" lsidName="Amphiglyphosema" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" rank="genus">Amphiglyphosema</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="76ABBDC4C00948FF43D533B0C52F7C17" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Afrostilba</taxonomicName>
. However, there are still species of Afrotropical 
<taxonomicName id="CA0C9E61293542901149B3F93AF299AE" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
of which we have not yet been able to examine the types, which may be 
<taxonomicName id="4B08C7AE32E19AC04475D6D2B500A580" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Afrostilba</taxonomicName>
or true 
<taxonomicName id="A2BDEA87D52715DF9970ABDC722A6597" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
, and these species are still listed under 
<taxonomicName id="07B1375B60F8EA8C6C9206E1601A7255" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5618387E930BA7B7D1FF8B74E18121B1" lastPageId="73" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="61D8805D5917F5950DE7D618F54847FA" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1525E18463C29F953A2F8D87F1429770" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Mesopleural triangle distinctly impressed, with both dorsal and ventral margins cleft, delimited by a sharp edge. Lateral pronotal carina present. Notauli present, well developed in nearly all species. Scutellar plate large, glandular pit in center. Hairy ring at base of syntergum absent; metasoma downturned towards ventral position. Most easily confused with 
<taxonomicName id="B47C182FAFA94C0122917FB9F4B9898E" authority="Förster, 1869" authorityName="Förster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Diglyphosema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diglyphosema" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Diglyphosema</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A4727324A3C8E865973EB1793E790017" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
; distinguished from these genera by the presence of a distinctly impressed mesopleural triangle, and downturned metasoma. In both 
<taxonomicName id="DDD161EFC7FB68FB0F666BAB150A32A8" authority="Förster, 1869" authorityName="Förster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Diglyphosema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diglyphosema" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Diglyphosema</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CC8B8DA08A869513391B767FC292AA4D" authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Gronotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gronotoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gronotoma</taxonomicName>
, the mesopleural triangle is present, but the dorsal and ventral margins are gently rounded, and the metasoma is directed more posteriorly. Distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="3C3CE57DC7DB8E86DC0DF1184E8118C2" authority="Lin, 1988" authorityName="Lin" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Eucoilidae" genus="Paradiglyphosema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paradiglyphosema" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Paradiglyphosema</taxonomicName>
by the possession in the latter of a genal carina and postero-lateral projections on the scutellum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A4F001DDD9FF4832359C75AB50416432" lastPageId="73" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Five species groups are recognized within the genus, all based on the morphology of the scutellum. This character system provides a wealth of taxonomic information, and from the hundreds of specimens examined for this paper, the characters appear to be stable through space and time. The most commonly encountered species group is the 
<taxonomicName id="719376FDC125ABF35F4D8F5839717CE6" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba nitida" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">
<pageBreakToken id="354522F74C3016CFE312B2433C8DE5AE" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" start="start">Afrostilba</pageBreakToken>
nitida
</taxonomicName>
group, characterized by having a distinctly concave dorsal surface of the scutellar plate. This is best seen in lateral view, and can be characterized as reminiscent of a gentle 
<normalizedToken id="069324C7B9D5941E847575C522AFD695" originalValue="‘wave’">'wave'</normalizedToken>
or 'ski 
<normalizedToken id="F57914EE104624F11ACE9E302CD368C2" originalValue="jump’">jump'</normalizedToken>
. From our examination of the type series of all of 
<bibRefCitation id="AB0664EDB5185B2ACBFE99F269857106" author="Quinlan, J" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Historical series" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" pagination="243 - 366" title="A key to the Afrotropical genera of Eucoilidae (Hymenoptera), with a revision of certain genera." volume="52" year="1986">
<normalizedToken id="C4BED252526E50F1A6233CE66E4F598A" originalValue="Quinlan’s">Quinlan's</normalizedToken>
(1986)
</bibRefCitation>
species, several species in this group will be synonymized in a more thorough treatment of the genus. The 
<taxonomicName id="B8D4B555DCE8F6A2CD88BD41E5F6869F" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba dubia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dubia">Afrostilba dubia</taxonomicName>
species group is characterized by having an extremely short, narrow scutellar plate, revealing much of the dorsal surface of the scutellum. Some specimens in this group approach an 
<taxonomicName id="5B911B63D0D6CEFDD4E51E9403B09F2C" authority="Quinlan" authorityName="Quinlan" class="Hexapoda" family="Figitidae" genus="Ealata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ealata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ealata</taxonomicName>
in appearance, but lack other characters of that genus. The 
<taxonomicName id="9D421CFC314D19D8E0020618537538C4" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba bucca" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bucca">Afrostilba bucca</taxonomicName>
species group is second in diversity to the 
<taxonomicName id="97E7A47D2AC6666C51B2AB16E18BDBEA" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba nitida" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">Afrostilba nitida</taxonomicName>
species group, and superficially looks similar. However, in the 
<taxonomicName id="55C759B8B768D66B32A051434F357448" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba bucca" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bucca">Afrostilba bucca</taxonomicName>
species group, the scutellar plate, in profile, is perfectly flat (wave or ski-jump shaped in the 
<taxonomicName id="D3E86FE1C705DF8B845D6385561DDC76" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba nitida" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">Afrostilba nitida</taxonomicName>
species group), with a large, deep glandular release pit. The last species group to be recognized here is the 
<taxonomicName id="EEC47FEB536FC2FAD5C686871A428BD0" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba fercula" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fercula">Afrostilba fercula</taxonomicName>
species group. On first glance, these species look similar to the 
<taxonomicName id="2598C3AD42D71BAEC66525A4FF42145C" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba bucca" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bucca">Afrostilba bucca</taxonomicName>
species group, however, species in the 
<taxonomicName id="C649FDC127FDB0A7F0E30EFEC1FDEF34" authority="Benoit, 1956" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Afrostilba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Afrostilba fercula" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fercula">Afrostilba fercula</taxonomicName>
group possess a very small, shallow, glandular release pit. The appearance of the scutellar plate is remarkable in that the rim of the plate appears enormous, when in fact, the rim is of normal width; it is the small glandular release pit contributing to this illusion.
</paragraph>
<caption id="28DC8D15F73CFA28C38A7DD2CD8BE655" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
